            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Joshua Novak\u2019s passion for public transit was born from its absence. Growing up in a sprawling Sacramento suburb, his world was defined by the automobile. He spent his teenage years feeling stranded, dependent on parents for rides and resenting the acres of asphalt that separated homes from shops and friends. This frustration fueled a fascination with thoughtfully designed cities, leading him to a Bachelor's in Urban Planning and Public Administration at UC Davis.\n\nHis career began with a junior planner position in Berkeley, but his ambition was always focused on the complex, maddening, and beautiful transit ecosystem of San Francisco. He joined the SFMTA twelve years ago, working his way up to Senior Transit Planner. His proudest professional achievement was his instrumental role in optimizing the service patterns for the Van Ness Bus Rapid Transit project\u2014a grueling, politically fraught process that left him with a few more gray hairs but a deep sense of accomplishment every time he rides that corridor.\n\nA key turning point in his personal life came seven years ago when a long-term relationship ended. His partner yearned for a house in Marin, a yard, and a two-car garage\u2014the very lifestyle Joshua had spent his life working to provide alternatives for. The amicable split solidified his commitment to an urban existence. Today, his social life is a tight-knit circle of fellow civic-minded professionals and neighborhood friends, often meeting for trivia at a Hayes Valley pub or for weekend bike rides across the Golden Gate Bridge.\n\nJoshua lives in a rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley, a neighborhood he adores for its walkability and central location. His daily 2.5-mile commute on the MUNI is both professional research and quiet time. He practices what he preaches, not having owned a car in over a decade. His dream is to see the Central Subway extended and to help pilot a new generation of light rail vehicles, further weaving the city together. For Joshua, improving San Francisco\u2019s transit isn't just a job; it's a mission to give the next generation the freedom of movement he never had as a kid."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the rough texture of the curb under his hands, age sixteen. His friend's beat-up sedan had broken down, and with it, his ride to the movies. The ticket felt useless in his pocket. It wasn't just missing the film; it was the suffocating feeling of being stranded, his world shrinking to the radius of a bicycle ride on scorching asphalt. In that moment of helpless frustration, a quiet vow formed: he would build a world where a simple breakdown didn't sever you from your life.\n\n2.\nTwelve years ago, on his first day at SFMTA, he stepped onto a pre-dawn N Judah train. He grabbed a metal pole, cool to the touch, and felt the familiar lurch as it dove underground. Surrounded by the quiet hum of a city waking up, he was no longer a tourist or a student, but a part of the system. The simple act of the commute felt like a profound liberation, the perfect antidote to his car-bound youth. This wasn't just a ride to work; it was arriving at his life.\n\n3.\nIt wasn't a fight, but a gentle surrender seven years ago. On their worn sofa, she described a garden in Marin, the sound of crickets, a two-car garage. He listened, picturing the life she deserved, and knew with a bone-deep certainty he could never live it. The sadness was immense, but underneath it was a quiet click of self-acceptance. He wasn't choosing a city over her; he was finally, fully choosing himself. The split cemented his path, turning his professional principles into a personal creed.\n\n4.\nThe ribbon-cutting was for the politicians. His real moment came two years ago, standing anonymously in a crowded accordion bus on the Van Ness BRT. He watched a nurse in scrubs, a student with headphones, and a family with groceries all share the space he helped create. There was no applause, just the smooth glide of the bus in its dedicated lane. A quiet, overwhelming wave of pride washed over him. He felt the weight of a thousand political battles lift, replaced by the simple reality of a promise kept.\n\n5.\nLast summer, halfway across the Golden Gate Bridge, he stopped his bike. His friends pulled up beside him, laughing, their faces flushed from the climb. Below, the bay glittered. To his right, the city he worked for and loved stood magnificent and dense. In that moment, wind-whipped and breathless, he felt a profound sense of rightness. This\u2014the\nfriendship, the freedom of two wheels, the iconic infrastructure holding them up\u2014was the connected, urban life he had truly built for himself."
